maybelater: <p>
After much struggle, I managed to track down the problem:<br />
</p>
<ol><li>Our specific plugin calls <code>wp_editor( '', 'tasty-recipes-editor', array( 'teeny' =&gt; true ) );</code>. This instance isn't ever rendered. Rather, we then steal <code>tinyMCEPreInit.mceInit['tasty-recipes-editor']</code> when we call <code>tinyMCE.init()</code> for our dynamic text fields.
</li><li>In the Classic Editor, TinyMCE is initialized via <code>WP_Editor-&gt;editor_js()</code>. However, TinyMCE is initialized in Gutenberg with <code>print_default_editor_scripts()</code>. The former makes the <code>tinyMCEPreInit.load_ext()</code> call while the latter does not.
</li><li>Gutenberg doesn't initialize external plugins globally on preinit, only when the Classic Block TinyMCE is initialized.
</li></ol><p>
I was able to work around this by filtering TeenyMCE init and always including our external plugin:<br />
</p>
<pre class="wiki">add_filter( 'teeny_mce_before_init', function( $settings, $editor_id ) {
	if ( 'tasty-recipes-editor' !== $editor_id ) {
		return $settings;
	}
	$external_plugins = array();
	if ( isset( $settings['external_plugins'] ) ) {
		if ( is_string( $settings['external_plugins'] ) ) {
			$external_plugins = json_decode( $settings['external_plugins'], true ) ? : array();
		} elseif ( is_array( $settings['external_plugins'] ) ) {
			$external_plugins = $settings['external_plugins'];
		}
	}
	$assets_path                    = dirname( dirname( __FILE__ ) ) . '/assets';
	$assets_url                     = plugins_url( 'assets', __DIR__ );
	$filepath                       = '/js/tinymce-plugin.js';
	$mtime                          = filemtime( $assets_path . $filepath );
	$external_plugins['tastylinks'] = $assets_url . $filepath . '?v=' . (int) $mtime;
	$settings['external_plugins']   = $external_plugins;
	return $settings;
}, 10, 2 );
</pre><p>
Closing this as <code>maybelater</code> as I don't think it's worth spending time fixing.<br />
</p>

